.TH "MAN" "1" "2026\-04\-11" "Winix" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
man \- display man pages
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]man\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] [\f[I]section\f[R]] \f[I]name\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Locates and renders a man page for \f[I]name\f[R].
Supports coloured output, clickable hyperlinks (OSC 8), and an optional
pager.
.PP
Man pages are searched in the following order:
.IP "1." 3
\f[B]Bundled\f[R] pages shipped with Winix tools (always available,
cross\-platform).
.IP "2." 3
\f[B]MANPATH\f[R] \(em directories listed in the \f[B]MANPATH\f[R]
environment variable.
.IP "3." 3
\f[B]Auto\-detected\f[R] system locations (\f[CR]/usr/share/man\f[R],
\f[CR]/usr/local/share/man\f[R], etc.
on Linux/macOS; no system locations on Windows).
.PP
Use \f[B]man \(enmanpath\f[R] to inspect the effective search path.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\(enno\-pager\f[R]
Print output directly to stdout without opening a pager.
.TP
\f[B]\(encolor\f[R]
Force coloured output (overrides \f[B]NO_COLOR\f[R]).
.TP
\f[B]\(enno\-color\f[R]
Disable coloured output.
.TP
\f[B]\(enwidth\f[R] \f[I]N\f[R]
Override output width in columns.
\f[I]N\f[R] must be at least 10.
When omitted, width is taken from MANWIDTH if set, otherwise from the
terminal width capped at 80 columns.
The 80\-column cap matches the effective behaviour of GNU man\-db (which
delegates rendering to groff, whose default width is 80) \(em set
MANWIDTH or pass \f[B]\(enwidth\f[R] explicitly to render wider.
.TP
\f[B]\-w\f[R], \f[B]\(enpath\f[R]
Print the path to the man page file and exit (do not render).
.TP
\f[B]\(enwhere\f[R]
Alias for \f[B]\(enpath\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]\(enmanpath\f[R]
Print the list of man page search directories and exit.
.TP
\f[B]\(enjson\f[R]
Write a JSON summary of the page metadata to stdout and exit.
.TP
\f[B]\(endescribe\f[R]
Print machine\-readable metadata and exit.
.TP
\f[B]\(enversion\f[R]
Show version.
.TP
\f[B]\-h\f[R], \f[B]\(enhelp\f[R]
Show help.
.SH EXIT CODES
.TP
\f[B]0\f[R]
Man page found and rendered (or \f[B]\(enpath\f[R] /
\f[B]\(enmanpath\f[R] output printed).
.TP
\f[B]1\f[R]
Man page not found.
.TP
\f[B]2\f[R]
Usage error (bad arguments).
.TP
\f[B]125\f[R]
Internal error.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
\f[B]MANPATH\f[R]
Platform\-separated list of directories to search for man pages,
prepended to auto\-detected locations.
The separator is \f[B]:\f[R] (colon) on Linux/macOS and \f[B];\f[R]
(semicolon) on Windows, matching the platform\(cqs PATH separator.
.TP
\f[B]MANWIDTH\f[R]
When set to a positive integer ≥ 10 and \f[B]\(enwidth\f[R] is not
given, used as the rendering width.
Otherwise the default applies (terminal width, capped at 80).
.TP
\f[B]MANPAGER\f[R]
The pager command to invoke for displaying rendered output.
May be a bare executable (\f[B]less\f[R]) or a full command line with
arguments (\f[B]less \-R\f[R], \f[B]less \-R \(enignore\-case\f[R]); the
value is passed to \f[B]/bin/sh \-c\f[R] on Linux/macOS and \f[B]cmd
/c\f[R] on Windows so any shell\-syntax is honoured.
Takes priority over \f[B]PAGER\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]PAGER\f[R]
Fallback pager command, consulted when \f[B]MANPAGER\f[R] is unset.
Same parsing rules as \f[B]MANPAGER\f[R].
If neither variable is set, man falls back (in order) to a sibling
\f[B]less\f[R] binary in the same directory, the \f[B]less\f[R] found on
\f[B]PATH\f[R], or a built\-in minimal pager.
.TP
\f[B]NO_COLOR\f[R]
If set, disables coloured output and clickable hyperlinks
(no\-color.org).
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP
.EX
man timeit

man 3 printf

man \-\-path timeit

man \-\-manpath

man \-\-no\-pager timeit

man \-\-color timeit | cat

man \-\-json timeit
.EE
